segments.text: Trying to find where I might go in terms of career was influenced by my brother, really, to consider fisheries.
We were both at San Diego State College at that time, and we were sort of looking at various alternatives.
And he happened to run across a booklet from the University of Washington that described the College of Fisheries at that time.
I guess it was a department.
And I became interested after I read the brochure.
And quite frankly, I thought fisheries had something to do with running fish hatcheries and things at that period of time.
And anyway, my wife and I came up here in 1946 and essentially got into the University of Washington.
And I guess that started my career into fisheries, which ultimately
sort of branched out into a broad range of fisheries and oceanographic activities.
Were you reared close to the sea?
Yeah.
I actually grew up in a number of seaports.
I was a small boy.
I lived out on Tatoosh Island, which is the furthest, most northwesterly island in the United States before Alaska was added, of course.
Lived out in the Hawaiian Islands.
And I guess as long as I could remember, it was in the water in one form or the other, either in a small boat or swimming.
And had my own outrigger canoe when I lived in the Hawaiian Islands.
We lived in Japan and the Philippines and always on the sea.
So I guess that there was an attachment and association with the oceans from a very young age.
What did you do in China during the war?
You just have intelligence service listed.
Well, the China story is rather an interesting one.
It's one that was ultimately written up and called the Rice Paddy Navy.
During World War II, Chiang Kai-shek did not really get along very well with certain elements of the U.S. government.
And as you recall, the only U.S. forces allowed in China were the 14th Air Force.
The relationship between the Air Force was quite good.
There were no U.S. ground forces in China.

Chang saw a need, however, apparently, for some American forces in terms of training, in terms of guerrilla-type activities, and through a very close friend he had in the Navy, Admiral Miles, an arrangement was set up to essentially have the Navy send in groups of their people
who were at least on paper transferred over to the Chinese National Forces.
And this became a group that worked in demolition, coastal observations, weather services, and were spread almost throughout China.
And that was my type of activity.
It was a broad range of intelligence type of thing and demolition and you might say running warfare.
No weather alerting then?
Because they also established a series of minerals.
Yes, we did.
As a component to our, wherever we had a group, we had about eight major groups stationed all the way from the Gobi Desert all the way down to southeast China.
We also had meteorologists with us, so we had meteorological units with us.
Sometimes they had to run like the rest of us, so they picked up their equipment and gear and moved from here to there.
Did you know Spillhouse when he was in China?
I did not know Spillhouse personally.
I did have a chance to meet with Chang and General Dai Li, which was sort of his, I guess, Gestapo of the Chinese system at that time, and other key Chinese officials.
But you were not suggesting that your activities in China had any direct effect upon taking you into, or back into the sea, or back to the sea?
No, no way.
I think it was just an interlude in my activities.
like most of our Army careers, an unnecessary evil, which occurred.
So now, when you leave then the University of San Diego, or San Diego State, and come to the University of Washington, did you enter graduate work then?
Undergraduate.
I had only had about, I guess I finished about a year and maybe one semester.
San Diego State was on the semester system.
And then I came up here, I think, in mid-semester and started in the fall of 1946, I believe, into the University of Texas.
Now, there wasn't even an undergraduate school of oceanography here at all in 1946.
It's yet to be organized.
So what did you major and work in?

Well, in essence, at that time, I essentially took largely fisheries with some oceanographic courses as a background, but I really did not take a great deal of work in the area of such a physical oceanography, chemical oceanography, until I got into graduate studies.
And with whom did you work?
In undergraduate work?
Undergraduate work.

Well, largely at that time I worked under old Dean Chapman, Webb Chapman, who was a very famous individual in the field of fisheries notionography, who was the dean of the college or the department at that time.
Later became one of the first head in the State Department for Fisheries in the United States in the post that was established there, and later was a
key element in the international affairs through the Van Camp Foundation.
He died several years ago, as you probably know.
He was the dean.
I guess the key professors that I worked under were Dr. Waylander, Dr. DeLacy.
I suppose those were the two key people that I was most closely associated with in the
my undergraduate career.
I did know Dr. Barnes fairly well at that time, because I did start going over and taking some courses from the oceanography department.
And Dr. Barnes was one of the old, well, been entrenched over there for a great number of years.
He was a teacher both when I was there as an undergraduate and when I came back almost a decade later into graduate studies.
After you received your degree in fisheries then, the first degree you received in fisheries, you joined the government service almost at once, did you not?

Right, but during my college years in the summer, really the first job I had in fisheries that really I sort of was a break-in sort of job for me and really led me into the ocean end of it rather into such areas as fish culture and that sort of area was that I
was stationed one summer down at Astoria, Oregon, under the Oregon Department of Fisheries.
And my job was, in essence, to beg rides on the trawl fish vessels to carry out a tragging program.

We had no research vessels that are owned at that time, and we used to put our, essentially, tagging boxes on board the back of a trawler if they had the proper pumps to get the water circulated into them.
get permission from the skipper to go on board and offer to help stand watches and help sort the catch as a part of the pay to go out and tag fish.
And that was sort of my first exposure really in terms of
ocean activity.
And believe me, it was one that I think that I'll never forget because I spent time on, you know, like about every boat that I could climb on, 30 or 40 different boats.
And if you want to see a wide variety of a different type of human life is to go on a fishing fleet, you know, everything from people that are drunks to college graduates to
people that can't say two words without swearing to some very sophisticated individuals.
It was a very diversified type of population.
One charge that's been levied really by colleagues of yours has been that one of the problems with the young oceanographers is they don't go to sea often enough.
Don't get their feet wet is the phrase that's usually used.
Would you agree with this?
Well, I think there's a place, of course,
in today's world that relates to the people that are associating with, let's say, the mathematical aspects of modeling that probably doesn't require that type of exposure.

But I think that if I had my druthers, I would like to think that all of my young people had at least been exposed to going to sea, both on commercial and research vessels, and had some appreciation of the quality of data
in the problems of operating at sea, the problems that the fishermen confront, because I do think it would give them a better perception of essentially that database they were working with.
And I think I somewhat resent a good number of the young people that come in to becoming oceanographers.

would like to sit and make all sorts of value judgments on the basis of the data and who have never been to sea and who have never seen the problems or don't have that sort of appreciation for what that data is likely to mean.
So do you work all of your summers now during this hour tagging off fishing vessels?
During that period of time?
Yeah.
I did only the first summer.
And then when I came back,
and graduated in 1950 from the university.
I came over to this building and started in a job, what they called at that time, a fishers gear engineer and gear specialist.
I've even forgotten the title, but some title of that sort.
Equipment and gear specialist.
In essence, which our job was an old group called exploratory fishing.
And exploratory fishing wasn't very scientifically oriented at that time.
period of time.
It was sort of go out and throw out the net and see if you can find fish in an area that essentially somebody else hasn't fished before, and somebody didn't realize there were resources in that area.
Of course, subsequent to that, over a period of perhaps five years, it became a very sophisticated type of activity.
But my first job was in this exploratory fishing, where we went out aboard both commercial

and research vessels, and in essence tried to find the animal complexes that weren't subject to commercial exploitation and to try to decide what latent resources were there for future use by the U.S. fishing industry and by the American public and the world in general.
How did you make contact with the Bureau of Fisheries in 1950?
Did you know someone over here?
I had a very good friend who had graduated the year before.
who'd come into the exploratory fishing group, a fellow named Don Powell.
And Don encouraged me to come with the exploratory fishing group as a good friend in college.
And I rather liked the sound of the adventurous nature of going out and carrying out sort of explorations in the ocean.
And he talked me into coming with the group.
How long did you spend at sea during this period?
Oh, boy.
period that I was with the government, and I think that was roughly about three and a half years that I was with them.
Maybe I have to look at my records, but I guess I was at sea pretty much a minimum of 100 to 140 days a year, so a lot of time at sea.
Now, you're right.
You spent about three, three and a half years with them.
And then you leave them and go on to look at something differently.
What did you look at and why?
Well, there was a couple of reasons I left then.
I left really because I was not happy with certain policies that were in terms of management that related to the then manager or director of the exploratory unit.

who I at that time felt took too much of a haphazard approach to carrying out the surveys and the activities, and that there was a failure to document the data properly and in the manner that it should be, and that we weren't making the range of observations that I thought felt were important and that we could make with really out any additional layout in terms of funds or effort.
And we sort of had a conflict.
He was a gentleman that had essentially
grown up without a scientific background.

I don't say that he didn't have some good qualities, because he did, but he didn't have any real appreciation for science, and I guess I was a scientist, and then our paths sort of collided in that sense, and I decided to look elsewhere, and at that time went over to the Washington Department of Fisheries to take charge of their commercial fish or ground fish studies.
And?
What was the Washington Department of Fisheries?
Washington Department of Fisheries is the state agency here in the state of Washington that's responsible for many of the fishing activities in the state of Washington.
And they have a small research group that essentially developed the database upon which to make decisions, which I became associated with.
They were also the enforcement officers
set up state regulations, govern the salmon fisheries, etc.
So, in effect, you're going from deep sea oceanography to sort of inland and coastal oceanography, aren't you?
Yeah, to an extent, except I asked to be associated with the offshore trawl fishery, which operated essentially from...
central Washington up to the northern tip of Vancouver, so I still had pretty much an ocean activity.
It was the small part, by the way, you're right, of the total research program.
Most everything else was associated with salmon and inshore activities.
It was the only sort of ocean program that the state was supporting, and I think I had two people that worked with me on that particular project.
Now, you stayed with this project how long?
Same with that project, roughly five years.
And really, I think it's the project that shaped my future outlook and dimensions in terms of where I might go.
Because again, I got some very earthy experience in that group.
My first job was to set up a central interview system
with the fishermen to set up a, in fact, I think it was the first application of information collected from a broad range of the fishing industry into the computer system.
Those computers were just getting into being.

And I saw the use of using the computer system of storing a great deal of both biological and statistical information, which is still in use, by the way, by the state in terms of making management decisions.
And through that interview system, one of the first job was to go down and actually interview every skipper that was landing his catches in the state of Washington.

In addition to the traditional things of organizing studies that related to tagging and migrations and population dynamics, I also had to set up a system of collecting basic raw material from the fishermen on which we would have a better basis to make judgments.
And I just think I learned a lot from fishermen.
I learned a lot from my exposure to these people and their leadership in the industry.
I learned a lot about the ocean.
I learned a lot about fish by going out onto their boats.
And I think that from that time on, I was wedded to a program in the oceans itself and in the sea.
OK. And do you do essentially this same job for five years?
My job was to direct this program.
I guess those five years I... Yeah, right.
And you were saying my job was essentially to... Yeah, my job was essentially to put together the scientific information, I guess, upon which the managers could make decisions.
And I guess that's when I really got into the publication there.
I began from...
to develop some very lengthy monograms that related to the ground fish and commercial fish complex or commercial fish complex off the coast here.
Their behavior phenomena that I could detect from the statistics that the fishermen were submitting to themselves.
In fact, one of the first, and I think one of the very good papers I've ever done was on the seasonal behavioral patterns of ground fish.

It resulted from my collection of about three years of the data from the commercial fisheries and then examining how the various species were moving in a bathymetric sense throughout the year, which was subsequently published as a major monograph.
And that's where that monograph came from.
I was going to ask that question you just answered.
It came from research done there.
So you think then the move into
I don't want to use the word academic oceanography because that's not even fair.
And first of all, that's not what you do.
But you think that the move into producing hard science in terms of publishing comes from this period right here?
I think that was the stimulus, yes.
That was the period.
And that's when I began to sort of reaffirm my attachments over at the university by going over
and reviewing the various papers I was developing with some of my old professors, with the people over there.
Well, that also answers another question.
The next question I was going to ask you, is this the beginning of the direction going back to graduate school?
Because you returned to graduate school rather late, as many of us did.
You know, I'm going to make a harsh statement here.
By the time I had finished five years, I had probably published as much in my field
Many PhDs have published sometimes in a career.
And I got a little tired of going to meetings and saying, but doctor so-and-so says.
It was quite obvious to me that that attachment to that degree carried a great deal of weight.
I think it's unfortunate in some instances, because it does.
We have 15 seconds later now.
I don't think you need to.
Where were we, by the way?
We were just finishing up the State of Washington.
Well, not really.
You were commenting that on publication, where we were.
And you were saying that it became a little exasperating to go to a meeting and discover that without a PhD that your comments didn't receive the credence they should have.
They didn't receive the weight that certainly some people who had a PhD and hadn't done any work in that field.
It was a little bit exasperating.
You're right.
And I finally said to somebody, I said, well, because that's the way they play the game, I'm going to go get back and get that shingle.
Yeah.
And so that's when you begin to make the decision to go back and take a PhD.
I was influenced, by the way, very strongly by my boss in Washington at that time.
That's just after I left fisheries and came back with the federal service.
I had a fellow named Stewart back there that just said, you know,
I think you ought to go back and get a PhD.
And as far as I'm concerned, the government will make time for you to go back and get it.
He said that until you do, you aren't going to be able to play the game with the big boys in the way you'd like to.
This must be 58, right?
That's right.
And what are you doing in 58?
58, I've left the Department of Fisheries again because I have sort of a history of this.

I'm fairly independent in my attitudes, and if I feel that I cannot honestly work for a manager and support his philosophies, then rather than grumble down at the bar, I go and essentially meet with that individual and say that, you know, tell him what the problem is.
If we can't rectify it, I essentially leave.
And when there was a new director of fisheries came on,

only Milo Moore that I'm still a very good friend in, but had certain policies in the way of using scientists more in the basis of to support political decisions rather than develop science that I just essentially couldn't live with.
And in essence, he and I had a confrontation.
And I decided that I wasn't going to prosper very much any longer under the Department of Fisheries.
left the Department of Fisheries along with many other good scientists.
At that time, there was a major sort of exodus from the Washington Department of Fisheries of perhaps 15 or 20 of their best scientists at that time for the same reasons.
He was an individual who felt that he didn't need scientists.
And where he did need them, he needed them to parrot what his philosophies were rather than what the data said.
And as a result, many people left.
I came back and started to work for, under the same individual, replacing, excuse me, the individual that got me into this business.
Mr. Powell had been here, went to Washington, and I came and replaced him and took over as sort of director of the exploratory fishing group here in 1958.
And that's when you decided, I take it then you must have gone to work on your Ph.D. part-time?
I guess it was about six months after I came back that I made the commitment.
And at that time, I started on a part-time basis.
And I think I only took one quarter off.
I had to have some regulation that related to residency period, and I had to take one
one quarter off.
But the remainder of that, I sort of, and it's not a very good way to go through a PhD program, but I struggled through a good number of years on sort of a part-time program.
Yeah, it is not a very pleasant way to receive a degree.
It's a lousy way.
And believe me, I don't encourage it because it is a stress on you and a stress on keeping your job going.
And I don't think you do quite the job that you could do that
if you were off on a full-time basis.
I don't think I suffered any in my grades or anything, but nevertheless, I could have done a better job.
Now, what were you doing in terms of job occupation at this time?

At that time, I was directing the exploratory group, which by that time, remember I said I wasn't happy with it when I left, allowed me to sort of provide a whole new philosophy of what exploratory fishing meant in terms of both answering questions
the interest of the academic community, at the same time providing valuable data to the industry upon which they could make decisions.

I was convinced both needs could be met, where my former boss felt that you really couldn't do the science because in order to tell a fisherman he could catch so many pounds of fish in certain areas, you could only handle it one way.
And I just didn't believe this.
And we developed a whole new philosophical base.
And then I was able to attract.
some real good scientists into the program.
I attracted Dr. Pereira into the program from the University of Washington, who became a mainstay of that program later.
Just a number of good scientists came into the program and it became, you know, and I have to say I have a bias, but it became a very productive group in terms of publications, in terms of
the fisheries communities throughout the northeastern Pacific and the oceanography of the area.
How long did you stay with this program?
I stayed with that program untiland here, you know, my dates are going to bother me, but I guess it was sometime in the late
Or in 1969, you become associate director of Fishers.
Okay, I was reaching for the date.
I knew it was in the late 60s.
I was there almost a decade, and that program in that period of time grew from roughly five individuals, which is what it was when I came to it.

to one that had about 25 individuals and a full-time vessel assignment to it, and was essentially making and providing the basic documents and scientific publications upon which we entered into our early negotiations with Japan for resolution of some of the high seas fishing programs in that area.
And it was these publications that served as the basis of our negotiations.
Well, that was almost the complete database

For our early work, when we had to go to Japan in terms of trying to re-establish a rational fishery for bottom fish off our coast in the Bering Sea, it was almost totally based on the work that we had done over the past decade.
Well, I was going to ask you something about Japanese fishing anyway, by the way.
And so I want to break away from chronological approach right now and ask you a couple of things.
Will American fishermen ever be able to compete with the Japanese?
Yes, they are now.

in part because the 200-mile limit provides certain preferential rights, and in part because the 200-mile limit, if properly managed... ...going to raise the abundance level of these fishes until they can be competitive.
In essence, one sees that happening now, by the way.
We were making a few comments about competition with Japan.
Oh, OK.
And I ask you if we can ever compete.
In certain areas.
I'm convinced it's going to be a long time where we can compete for low-priced, high-volume bottom fish like pollock, like redfish, like codfish.

But for certain key target species like the crustacean complex, I'm going to forecast within a decade we're going to be taking utilities in the full surplus that's available in the Bering Sea of all the crabs, of all the shrimp.
That fishery is just booming right now.
The fact is it increased 100% in one year.
The ex-vessel value of the raw material taken out of the Bering Sea for crabs this last year was close to $80 million, U.S. And so the foreigners are going to be out of business.
They're just not going to be there.
Other species of finfish, of course halibut, there's no problem.
The one I see us moving into very rapidly is black cod, which is a high-valued local species here, which has produced about 60 million pounds, which has largely gone to Japan.
which my guess is we'll be reducing the total potential of that also within the next 5 to 10 years.
That fishery is growing very rapidly.
We're now competitive.
We have the gear.
We have the boats.
The price is up to a range where our fishermen can afford to go out and catch it.
